Kendrick’s GNX album can be seen as a personal reckoning with not just his past but with an ancient spirit that has been influencing humanity long before his time. His acknowledgment of being “reincarnated” is, in this context, a metaphor for the return of this age-old force within him, leading to his internal spiritual conflict. While Kendrick may believe he’s experiencing reincarnation, it’s more likely that he’s confronting the same spiritual battle that has been fought by countless others before him—echoing themes from the Bible like Lucifer’s fall, the fall of man, and the eternal struggle between light and darkness.

His struggle with fame, power, and addiction echoes Lucifer’s fall from grace—tempted by pride, desire, and control over others. The repeated themes of manipulation and the pursuit of power in Kendrick’s narrative align with Lucifer’s desire for autonomy and supremacy.

Average brain size is not the same in all human populations. Average cranial capacity in Europeans is about 1362 ccs; 1380 in Asians, 1276 in Africans. It’s about 1270 in New Guinea. Generally there is a trend with latitude – brain volume is lowest near the equator. And no, despite Gould’s bushwa, there is nothing especially difficult about measuring brain volume. Direct measurement of a healthy brain is best; but that is now done, using magnetic resonance imagery, and the results are about the same – a mean black-white difference of about 1 standard deviation.\r

Graduate students in anthropology generally don’t know those facts about average brain volume in different populations. “Squabble Up” by Kendrick Lamar is an intricate and combative piece, showcasing Lamar’s unparalleled lyrical prowess and his ability to weave personal history, cultural critique, and rivalry into a cohesive narrative. As a master of self-reflection and confrontation, Lamar revisits his ongoing feud with Drake, addressing themes of competition, betrayal, and his journey to artistic supremacy.

The song’s first verse sets the stage with sharp critiques and coded references, calling back to their collaborative history and its subsequent unraveling. Kendrick indirectly revisits his explosive “Control” verse, where he declared his dominance over his peers, marking the genesis of his rivalry with Drake. In “Squabble Up,” Kendrick underscores how their shared trajectory diverged into a competitive squabble, with fame and ego driving a wedge between camaraderie and respect.

The chorus reinforces Kendrick’s defiance, brimming with imagery of battle and survival. His declarations of resilience and triumph nod to his earlier works like DAMN. and To Pimp a Butterfly, where he explored the duality of vulnerability and power. Here, Kendrick reclaims his throne, undeterred by industry politics or public perception, a sentiment reminiscent of his track “King Kunta,” where he dissected power dynamics and authenticity.

The second verse digs deeper into the psychological toll of success. Lamar questions the sincerity of his contemporaries, reflecting his constant battle with trust and betrayal. Echoing sentiments from Mr. Morale & The Big Steppers, he portrays fame as both a reward and a curse, an idea he’s often explored in songs like “U” and “Feel.” His personal grievances are interwoven with broader critiques of an industry that thrives on competition, forcing relationships into transactional and often fragile dynamics.

The bridge provides a rare glimpse into Lamar’s vulnerability, as he grapples with the emotional costs of his journey. This introspection harkens back to tracks like “Sing About Me, I’m Dying of Thirst,” where Lamar vulnerably dissected his fears of legacy, mortality, and self-worth. The somber tone in “Squabble Up” underscores his awareness of the sacrifices he’s made for greatness.

In the outro, Kendrick reasserts his place as the preeminent voice of his generation. He dismisses the distractions of rivalries, emphasizing his focus on the bigger picture: his craft, his impact, and his legacy. This conclusion mirrors the sentiments of “Alright” and “Duckworth,” where Lamar reminds listeners that his journey has always been about more than just music—it’s about survival, purpose, and transcendence.

“Squabble Up” is a masterclass in lyrical storytelling, connecting dots from Lamar’s past and present to illuminate his ever-evolving narrative. For die-hard fans, the song serves as both a reminder of his brilliance and a testament to his ability to rise above the noise, cementing his legacy as one of hip-hop’s most introspective and uncompromising artists.

I have listened to the album all the way through one time. Now Ill just give my initial thoughts which will certainly change in areas as I listen to the album more and spend more time with individual elements. This is the first time a Kendrick album has not grabbed me from the start. Wacced out Murals feels like a late to mid album cut instead of an opening track. The first half of this track list is incredibly bland in both lyrical content and production. You could play the instrumental to those first six songs and think you are listening to the same song the whole time. Production is evident early on, this is probably Kendricks worst produced album of his career. This is evident on a song like Luther where the female feature is drowned out and Kendrick gives you one of his worst lyrical performances in recent memory. The highs are high, the lows are low. My initial rating is a 7.2.
